Onion endangered: Three cheetah cubs born in Iran
The world's fastest animal falls victim to brutal hunts, droughts and deadly traffic accidents across the Islamic Republic •
As a result, their numbers dropped to less than 20 cheetahs.
Three Asian cheetah cubs recently emerged into the world's air in the Islamic Republic of Iran.
This is a rare birth, which only slightly improves the tragic condition of the endangered animal in the country following droughts, poachers and fatal traffic accidents.
This is the first birth of a cheetah in captivity in Iran.
It should be noted that the Islamic Republic is one of the last countries in the world where cheetahs still live in the wild.
The Iranian news agency IRNA reported that the veterinary team, which trusts the Toran National Park in the northern Semnan province, decided on a captive cesarean birth.
It is also noted that fewer than 20 cheetahs have been documented in recent times in seven different counties in the country.
Following the danger of their extinction, the United Nations put into practice a protection plan for them back in 2001.
Now, Iran hopes that the new cubs can bring about an increase in the cheetah population in the future.
Last January, Iran's deputy minister for environmental affairs, Hassan Akbari, said the country's cheetah population had dramatically reduced from 100 cheetahs in 2010 to just 12 cheetahs.
“Their situation is dire in the extreme,” Akbari said, noting that cheetahs have fallen victim to droughts in their living areas, hunting and even traffic accidents.
The cheetah is considered the fastest animal in the world capable of reaching speeds of about 100 km/h.
Cheetahs can be found in various places across the globe, from India to Senegal in West Africa.
Spotify wants to upgrade your car: we tested the Car Thing
Quietly, Spotify has begun to try its luck in the hardware world as well •
After years of development - Car Thing was unveiled and launched as a small experiment in the US •
We put our hands on the first device in Israel.
Vision: Make your old vehicles smart
The Car Thing is Spotify's first hardware product, and was built specifically to provide a solution for people with older vehicles.
A few weeks ago, I got an initial opportunity to try the new product, which is currently available only to individual experimenters in the US, here in Israel.
For me, the timing of the delivery was outstanding, as our home vehicle broke down and we had to drive for several days with a replacement vehicle with an old system.
After two weeks of toying around, I realized how the Car Thing could easily become an integral part of many people's system.
And on the other hand, with a long waiting list and uncertainty regarding a global launch, I believe that many will already prefer to use other solutions.
From idea to reality
Somewhere in 2018, Spotify users began to receive an interesting offer in their email box - the possibility of purchasing a new device with voice control and fourth-generation connectivity, which will turn any old car system into a smart one.
Rumors slowly waned until a year later, when the Financial Times website revealed that the company plans to soon introduce a new car product that simulates a smart radio with Bluetooth connectivity.
A few months later, these rumors returned to the headlines again after the music service updated with the mode of the vehicle - the same one that we know today from the app - that is activated as soon as the smartphone detects a connection to the system in the car.
Two years have passed since then.
After countless rumors and leaks, Spotify unveiled “Car Thing” last April, its smart system for vehicles.
Spotify has chosen to release the new device in a very limited way, with a long waiting list and many delays when it comes to shipments.
So of course, right after the press conference she held, I went onto the site and signed up.
Two months later, the long-awaited announcement arrived.
A re-connection to the site will buy me the opportunity to purchase the device with a little surprise - it will not cost me anything.
After another month of waiting, the messenger finally knocked my door, accompanied by a small box with the Spotify logo on it.
The Car Thing
First and foremost, Spotify's device has greatly impressed me with its build quality.
And a slightly smaller than my iPhone 11 and features a big, bright, sharp touch screen on its front than I expected.
Also, you will find next to the screen a round button and a dial that you can rotate to navigate through the interface screens.
And despite the huge dial, which you can see in the photos, the Car Thing manages to maintain a relatively flimsy profile and not stand out too much from the dashboard.
Personally, I would prefer that the company allowed the activity of the dial to be changed so that I could control the volume of the smartphone, since I can also navigate using the touch screen.
Perhaps this will be possible in a future version update.
The device comes in a small, minimalist cardboard box, which includes, among other things, a USB Type C cable and various adapters to install it.
Many of you probably remember how in the past we used to disconnect the radios and hide them in a drawer after leaving the car.
The Car Thing undoubtedly brings back that feeling with its build form.
All adapters were connected to the body of the device using a magnet that was very strong, which prevented it from falling even when driving on dirt roads.
On top of that, along the entire top you can find small buttons, which can be easily configured to play various playlists or podcasts.
By long pressing one of the buttons while hearing, or using a request from the voice assistant, I set up some playlists that I hear frequently and the radio show I listen to every morning on the go.
In doing so, the feature made me feel that the Car Thing is more like a car radio than an extension of my smartphone.
From old car to smart car
After a fairly simple physical setup, I plugged the Car Thing into power.
I was pleasantly surprised by the set-up process.
The instructions were clear, the connection to the Spotify app took less than 5 minutes, and a few moments later I reached the home screen.
In fact, the device connects to the smartphone through Bluetooth and controls the application like a remote, and therefore can copy all the information about our account from it.
That means you will still have to connect your smartphone to your car, either via Bluetooth or AUX cable in order to hear the music.
The home screen is familiar to all users of the application, since like the application on the smartphone, it places emphasis on the photos of albums and playlists.
Also, on the home screen, like the one in the app, you can find music recommendations according to your tastes, the search screen and your personal library.
As already mentioned, you can navigate between the different screens using the touch screen or using the manual caliper.
What's more, you can at any given moment call the device's voice assistant by saying “Hey Spotify”.
Using it, you can play songs, playlists, albums and even search for podcasts.
From Sony she quite easily recognized my voice even when the music was playing in the background and the air conditioner blew directly on the device.
This is probably thanks to the four microphones installed at the top.
It is important to note that at the moment the voice assistant does not support Hebrew, and as of the time of publication of the article, there is no information about when such an update will arrive.
So is it worth waiting for him?
My experience of using the device has been great, which is a positive surprise to me considering it is still in an initial release phase.
Even intensively used on long trips, the device continued to work smoothly without disconnecting from my smartphone.
Still, occasionally a small stutter is recorded in the interface, but I believe Spotify will handle such bugs with future version updates.
It is evident that the Swedish company has worked on it a lot in recent years, and among the different versions that have leaked online during this period, the design of the final product is probably my favorite.
Still, when I saw the Car Thing for the first time, I wondered who exactly the company was trying to designate it for.
After all, his activity comes down to controlling the application on a smartphone, and not much beyond that.
What is it different from buying a car stand for a few shekels and plugging it in so that the smartphone is closer to us when driving?
That question is reinforced when considering that iPhones and Android devices are much more powerful than Spotify's, and most times will buy the user much more functionality.
Despite all this, as I used the Car Thing more and more, I realized how it could improve the driving experience.
Being able to see the Waze on my smartphone screen and control the music on a completely different screen is one I've come to appreciate over the past two weeks.
One question remains - will Spotify even launch the device to the general public?
And if so, will it also be launched here in our small country?
The Swedish company is not currently telling much.
It hasn't even shared how many experimenters for the device it currently operates around the world, and how much it plans to add in its limited launch in the United States.
The only thing we know for sure is the price that is expected to be $79 (about NIS 255).
Meanwhile, the Car Thing provides an initial glimpse into a concept Spotify has been trying to crack for years.
Spotify Israel said there is currently no information about a plan to launch the device in Israel
