Have you recruited a Talent for the company?
That way, keep competitors not “snatching” it for you.
The economy is still in a labor market largely dominated by workers, and this is about two times true when it comes to the most desirable workers - the Talents •
Here are some tips to help you keep it in the workplace
.
Despite the increase recorded in the past month, the unemployment rate in Israel continues to be among the lowest in the world, and in the top 10 among OECD countries, with a rate of 3.5% (150.6,000 unemployed, according to CBS).
That is, the economy is still in a labor market that is largely controlled by workers and this is true for two times when it comes to the most desirable workers — the Talents.
When it comes to those professionals and managers who are proven centers of knowledge, experience, and ability — the trends in the labor market indicate that the competition for them, the Talents as they are called by employers, is still in full force.
This means for employers is that in the current labor market situation they do not have the luxury of resting on their laurels even a minute after the recruitment of a coveted Talent, since once he enters the company gates, another company will already try to snatch it to it.
That is, the competition for the Talents is so fierce that even after their enfranchisement they will continue to receive a multitude of tempting job offers, with 30% of employees actually leaving only about a month from the receipt of the job and the beginning of the job.
That is why intelligent employers will immediately move from the mobilization phase of the Talent to its preservation phase, when the road begins first and foremost by preparing in advance and taking creativity already in the process of its absorption.
An efficient, structured and thoughtful reception process will make Talent enthusiastic about its new workplace from day one and even look forward to the next.
Here are some tips on how to prepare and manage a proper reception process that will help preserve the new Talent:
It's no secret - sharing and readiness of the organization |
Share the factors that will work with him on his recruitment, explain to them why he is vital and important for the company and the job, and how you see his contribution.
A new employee who arrives where he is expected and understood his worth, will feel welcome and will strive to prove the expectations placed by a son.
Knowledge is Power - Coordination of Expectations |
Already on the first day, make a call to coordinate expectations with the Talent.
Get to know his professional background and see where he sees himself in the future, so you can introduce him to the diverse and unique tools that you and the workplace can provide him to get there.
We are all people — personal recognition
During the reception days try to get to know the Talent beyond its professional qualities and be interested in his hobbies and interests.
A new employee who shows interest in him and allow him to realize and express himself beyond the limits of his position will appreciate it and want to maintain it.
Curiosity advances |
Already in the absorption phase, you can create an attractiveness that will make the Talent want to integrate quickly.
Do this not necessarily by a discourse of bonuses and benefits, but by exposing it to an exciting field or interesting technology, as these kinds of stimuli for creativity lead to curiosity and growing interest in the workplace.
Also, encourage the Talent to voice his thoughts and opinions to the various projects in the company and make it clear to him that they are important to the organization.
The author is the CEO of Manpower Israel — the largest placement and manpower company in Israel
Electrification in the pocket: the cost of not closing the coal stations in June - NIS 1 billion
Report of the Knesset Research and Information Center: The failure to close the coal-fired stations at a date set in June 2022 is estimated to be NIS 1 billion
• IEC: “The policy on the use of fuels is dictated first and foremost by the Ministry of Energy”
.
The economic cost for not closing the coal-fired stations at a date set in June 2022 is estimated to be NIS 1 billion for 2022, a report by the Knesset Research and Information Center reveals.
According to the report, this cost is embodied in the consumer electricity tariff, which, as we have said, is expected to increase in the coming months due to the cost of coal.
In 2023, an additional excess amount of coal use of about 900,000 tons is expected in 2023, so this will result in an additional cost to the electricity economy for not closing the coal-fired stations, assuming that the price of natural gas remains significantly lower than the price of coal.
The report said that the reduction of about 1 billion shekels in the electricity tariff in 2022 was a 4% reduction in the electricity rate for the household consumer.
That is, the economic cost of not closing the stations is about NIS 1 billion, and the total amount that the consumer could have had is 4%.
It should be noted that in the framework of the electric power reform, among other things, it was decided to create a subsidiary of the IEC, which would build natural gas-powered units designed to replace the 4-1 coal-fired units at the Orot Rabin site.
Following this decision, a government decision was passed in July 2018, which stipulates that the operation of the coal-fired production units 4-1 at the Orot Rabin power plant should be discontinued.
Schedules have been set in the decision, so that the construction of the first natural gas unit will begin in January 2020 and its operation will begin in June 2022, and accordingly, the 4-1 coal production units will also cease to operate at this time.
The IEC said in response: “The policy on the use of fuels is dictated first and foremost by the Department of Energy.
In accordance with the Ministry's decisions, a policy has been implemented in Israel for several years of reducing the use of coal to the minimum possible even when the price of coal is lower than the price of gas.”
Paying the price: everything you need to know ahead of interest rate rises
Constantly decrees: Next week the interest rate on the shekel is expected to rise by half a percent •
How expensive will the mortgage payment be?
And what is recommended to do? •
All the answers
The worsening inflation in Israel, which has already reached a rate of more than 4% in the past year, will force the Bank of Israel to raise its interest rate on the shekel as early as next week.
Analysts' estimates speak of a raise rate ranging from 0.25% to 0.5%.
If interest rates do rise by half a percent, it will already be 1.25%, the highest level for nine years.
This, after for years the interest rate in the economy was close to zero.
The sharp increase in the interest rate makes mortgage repayments hundreds more precious and is drastically burdensome on households.
With the help of Shai Bundle, a mortgage expert, we examined how much more we would pay and what we should do right now.
If the interest rate rises by half a percent - how expensive will the monthly payment on the mortgage be?
In a mortgage of NIS 1.2 million, consisting of a 40% prime interest rate route, the monthly repayment will cost NIS 125.
How expensive was the average mortgage since the beginning of the year?
Since the beginning of the year, this is a significantly sharper rise.
This is because interest rates in the other routes that make up a mortgage (and not just in the prime route) have also risen - in an index-linked course and in the fixed-interest trajectory.
If the interest rate does rise by half a percent, the cost would amount, according to Bundle's estimate, at 620 shekels in a mortgage of about 1.2 million shekels.
The prime route (40% on this route) will complete a cost of about NIS 280, assuming that there will be an increase of another 0.5% next month.
The index-index-index-index-variable interest rate (26.7% in this route) will complete a cost of about NIS 120.
The fixed-interest rate course - not indexed (33.3% in this route) will be 220 shekels more expensive.
So what is recommended to do today?
For those who have a mortgage most indexed, Bundle recommends considering recycling for non-indexed routes.
For mortgage takers whose monthly repayments have increased significantly for them and it is difficult for them to meet repayments - he recommends looking at recycling a mortgage and redeploying it for a longer period of time.
This, to reduce payments despite the increase in interest, since it is always better to meet repayments and not be insolvent.
Regarding new mortgage takers - he highly recommends that you familiarize yourself with the different routes and adapt the mortgage to their financial capabilities.
So even in the future when interest rates drop they will be able to do mortgage recycling with a minimum of early repayment fees.
For buyers of apartments from a contractor - Bundle recommends making payments to the contractor and taking out a mortgage now.
It must be taken into account that the “Construction Inputs Index” raises the price of the property significantly even after the purchase contract is signed.
The housing input price index increased 6.6% over the past year.
Against the background of the cost of this measure, the other day, the Banking Superintendency announced that it was considering the creation of a mechanism that would allow the indexation to be included within mortgages, but the final decision on the matter has not yet been made.
The price of fuel is expensive - and Israelis will have to pay more than 8 shekels per liter in July
The Ministry of Energy announced that the new price per liter of 95-octane gasoline will be NIS 8.08
At the same time, the reduction of half NIS per liter in the tax on diesel fuel will be extended until the end of 2022
Decade record: The price of gasoline will leap by 36 penny per liter - and will be more than 8 shekels per liter from July 1.
The new price per liter of 95-octane gasoline will be 8.08 and those wishing to enjoy full service will be required to pay an additional 21 penny per liter.
At the same time, the reduction of half a shekel per liter in diesel tax will be extended until the end of 2022 - according to the Tax Authority.
As already mentioned, the increase in price is due to the continued rise in oil prices, against the background of the war between Russia and Ukraine and the increase in the dollar rate.
If it weren't for the half-shekel discount subsidized by the government since April, the price of gasoline would have passed the all-time high - NIS 8.25 per liter.
The validity of the discount ends at the end of July and the Tax Authority and the Treasury are currently promoting the publication of a decree extending the reduction in the tax on gasoline, which stands at half a shekel per liter, until August 9.
Also, starting on August 10, a further reduction of another half shekel will be set, so that only from this date the price of a liter of gasoline will decrease by one shekel until November 15, 2022.
This was reported from the Tax Authority.
“We have reached a situation where I can't remember five months in a row of excess in state income.
We started a few months ago with the issue of reducing the tax on diesel.
We have been working for a week on extending in four months the excise tax, gasoline and diesel - instead of half shekel to shekel.
It's good for the industry and the citizen.
If we lower, it will affect inflation, lower production and ease the cost of living.
As finance minister, despite the election campaign, I intend to focus first of all on that,” Minister Lieberman said at the Hurwitz Conference on Economics and Society of the Israel Democracy Institute.
To date, more than half of the price of gasoline is the taxes charged by the government (excise tax and VAT) - and this is a high rate of taxation compared to most developed countries.
The price of fuel has a dramatic impact on the cost of living in the economy - because it affects both household and business expenses, prices for public transport and air travel, transportation costs and more.
For the third time in a row: Ashdod - the friendliest city for business
Petah Tikva came second in the Ministry of Economy's Doing Business Rankings •
After them: Rehovot, Ashkelon and Rishon LeZion •
“Corona stressed the importance of local government in developing business”
.
Ashdod is the friendliest city for small and medium-sized businesses.
For the third year in a row, the Local Authorities Doing Business Index found by the Small and Medium Businesses Agency of the Ministry of Economy and Industry, which ranked local authorities.
In second place is the city of Petah Tikva and in third place Rehovot.
They are located in order: Ashkelon, Rishon LeZion, Tel Aviv-Jaffa, Haifa, Ramat Gan, Holon, Beersheba, Jerusalem, Bat Yam, Netanya and Bnei Brak.
The agency compiles the Local Authorities Index.
This is the fifth time and aims to serve as a working tool for the local authority, as it allows each authority to compare its performance to other authorities in a variety of parameters, as well as analyze its performance in the areas in which it is active.
The index is based on a few parameters examined in each authority, which examine the level of “friendliness” of the Authority for businesses in its field.
The index divides the authorities into three size groups according to the number of inhabitants, since a local authority of up to 50,000 residents is not comparable to a local authority of more than 150,000 residents.
TA has surged this year
The index is updated once a year and weighs four different ratings in each local authority: business satisfaction, accessibility to tenders, accessibility of information and property taxes.
The ranking shows that Ramat Gan dropped from second to eighth place, Bat Yam dropped from fourth to 12th place and Netanya dropped from fifth to 13th place.
A drop in the rating does not mean that the Authority's business service has deteriorated, and in many cases it is due to the fact that other authorities' service for businesses has improved more and they have increased in the rankings, while the authority has declined in the ranking has improved its services for businesses less.
Among the most ranked are Petah Tikva, who rose from sixth to second place, and Rehovot, who rose from 12th to third place.
Tel Aviv, which dropped from fourth to 11th place in 2019, improved in 2021 and rose to sixth place.
“Business - Growth Engine”
The ranking shows that Nof Galilee leads local authorities with between 50 and 150,000 residents.
This is followed by Kiryat Motzkin, Mata Binyamin, Modiin-Maccabim-Reut, Kfar Saba, Ra'anana, Nahariya, Karmiel, Afula and Hod Hasharon.
In 28th and last place is Tiberias.
“The measure aims to encourage local authorities to facilitate small and medium-sized businesses, starting from the date of opening the business and throughout its activities with the authorities,” says Minister of Economy and Industry, Orna Barbibai.
“Businesses are a significant growth engine for the Israeli economy and are responsible for about 50% of the business product and about 60% of the employed in the economy.
The development of small businesses is in the public interest of all of us, but the local authority has a direct impact on the businesses located in it.
The corona underscored the importance of local government and we saw that authorities who acted and encouraged the promotion of small businesses and found creative solutions for them, became the first governmental interface for them.”
Ran Koithi, director of the Agency for Small and Medium Businesses at the Ministry of Economy and Industry, adds: “Local authorities have a key and fundamental part in the ability of businesses in their fields to thrive and flourish.
In the last two years, in which we are dealing with the coronavirus crisis, authorities have greater weight in helping businesses survive in their field and survive at all.”
2021 By mail: 20 packages per household - and a leap in their weight
46.6 million packages arrived in Israel during 2021 - similar to 2020 •
The average weight per pack stands at 435 grams - a jump of 36% compared to 2020 •
Busiest month: December, when the average package weight stood at 524 grams.
In 2021, 46.6 million mail packages arrived in Israel, almost 20 packages on average per household - according to the data from Israel Post that reached Israel Hayom.
The amount of packages arrived in 2021 is similar to 2020, in which 46.5 million packages arrived in Israel, and lower than 2019, in which 61.6 million packages arrived.
However, this year there has been a jump of more than 36% per year in the weight of packages coming from abroad.
In 2021, 20,253 tons of products arrived in Israel from abroad, a jump of 36% from 14,860 tons in 2020, and 16,743 tons in 2019.
Changes in consumption habits
The average weight per package has soared by 60% in two years - from 272 grams in 2019 to 435 grams in 2021.
The surge in the weight of packages is mainly influenced by two major trends, both from the seller and the buyer side: the largest overseas shopping sites unite items into one shipment and no longer ship each product from the “shopping basket” in separate packaging.
On the part of the Israeli consumer, the rapid delivery of shipments, within a few days of ordering, supports the purchase of more everyday products such as clothing and gifts, which buyers want to receive near the purchase.
Also in 2021, as in 2020 and 2019, the month when the most overseas packages reached the highest weight and the highest number of items was December, with 4.2 million packages with a total weight of 2,200 tons.
In December, the average weight per package was 524 grams, 20% higher than the annual average weight.
Black Friday effect
More packages arrived in December than any other month, probably following the November shopping holidays, such as Chinese Singles Day, Black Friday, and Cyber Monday.
The largest orders begin to arrive in Israel between one and two weeks after buying.
Study: Most salaried in economy not aware that tax refunds can be obtained
Many employees deserve money from the state, which can reach tens of thousands of shekels.
Have you changed jobs?
Did you go to the LT?
Have you moved from the city to the settlement?
You may be entitled to receive a considerable amount in a simple procedure •
All the details - in the interior
Most tenancies are unaware of the fact that they are entitled to tax refunds, which can add up to high amounts.
The state comptroller noted in a report two months ago that two million employees are eligible for tax rebates of NIS 3.6 billion, which means you should also check whether you are eligible to receive tax returns.
Many tenancies can receive a high amount, as four out of five tenancies are eligible for tax returns.
In practice, on the other hand, serve several tens of thousands of tenancies per year.
If you think that these funds have gone down the drain anyway, think again: Salaries can apply to the IRS for refunds for back six years.
Tax:On has conducted in-depth research among 4,000 of its customers regarding tax returns during 2020.
The company has over 30,000 customers, so the sample reflects their dispersion in terms of population groups and in terms of gender, ages and geography.
The data shows that during 2020, due to the outbreak of the coronavirus crisis and the expenditure of hundreds of thousands of employees to the NIS, there have been a number of significant changes, centered on a 15% increase in the average return rate for a home of NIS 4,300 per year.
The reason is that the salary is lower than salaries and therefore a gap is created between what the employee paid as tax and what he actually needs.
By the way, the highest refund received in 2020 by a customer of the company was NIS 121,054 for repayments over the last 6 years.
What can I get a tax return for?
One reason to get tax refunds is a change in the workplace.
For 81% of people who changed jobs during the year, a tax return is generated for an average amount of NIS 2,943.
Another reason is maternity leave.
The data shows that 74% of women who gave birth and spent on maternity leave over 16 weeks were eligible for reimbursement at an average of NIS 3,538 for that year
Another reason for reimbursement is donations.
100% of people contributing and paying taxes were reimbursed.
Another factor for reimbursement is the failure to register credit points for alimony. 63%
The divorcee did not update a credit point for alimony, so the tax return for each year that has not been updated, such a credit point is NIS 2,616.
Due to unemployment - expenditure for the ILT: 93% of those leaving for the sick or unemployment and who earned over NIS 12,000 received a tax refund of NIS 4021 for the same year.
Other reasons for tax returns are: reimbursement for life insurance payments, life insurance on a mortgage, reimbursement of a qualifying return, reimbursement for losses on securities, failure to register credits to a man for childbirth and distribution of tax returns by geographical place.
- 94% of people who deposited for personal life insurance or for taking out a mortgage were entitled to a tax refund.
In the examination conducted on every NIS million 25-year mortgage, the cumulative tax return for the period is above NIS 20,000 for the entire term of the mortgage
100% of those who move to a qualifying settlement received a tax refund for the year of relocation, since confirmation of residency in a qualifying locality is granted only after 12 months from the date of the resident becoming a qualifying resident, thus in fact the first year full tax is paid.
79% of customers holding securities were eligible for the refund of said years tax.
However, those who hold securities are important to check every year since losses are not rolled out from year to year but only through the filing of a report.
56% of men who have a child do not register credits in the year of birth on the pay slip.
The repayment rate can reach tens of thousands of shekels over 6 years.
This is a phenomenon that exists mainly in the Arab sector.
Tax:on CEO Tal Carmon: “The coronavirus crisis has caused the salaried public in Israel to become much more active.
He takes an interest, checks and demands what he deserves in refunds from the IRS.
It turns out that the meeting at home, in the IDF or after the dismissal, of hundreds of thousands of Israelis for months on end, made many employees look into what they deserve from the country.
It is important to know that today all procedures for receiving tax returns can be done digitally, easy and simple, without the bureaucracy that has deterred many in the past.”
Employment Market: Fewer Job Applicants, More Wages
Alljobs report in summary 2021: top of demand - Jobs without experience •
The volume of jobs offered increased by 50% •
“Looking for a job, but not storming the market”
In the year that just ended, there was a 15% drop in the number of resumes sent, and an average of only 23 candidates faced each position, compared to 41 applicants in the previous year, according to a report by the UlJobs website in summary 2021, on the coronavirus crisis and its effects on the labor market in Israel.
According to the report, job seekers were primarily interested in job openings such as administration and sales, for which 1,738,485 resumes were sent.
However, the jobs without experience led to the top of demand with more than 38 thousand searches - probably following the return of young people with no professional experience to search for immediate employment, at the end of the applicable payments.
The number of searches for sales and administration was 35 thousand and 32,000 (respectively), drivers and couriers had 11,000 searches, and the conservators had slightly fewer than 9,000 searches.
On the other hand, despite the coronavirus crisis, wages in 2021 rose 2% compared to 2020, and the average salary in Israel was 11,675 gross shekels.
The monthly salary in the software field was an average of NIS 17,915, and in information systems analysis, it was 17,140 shekels.
However, between the center and the periphery there was a wage gap of more than 2,000 shekels: in the center of the country it was 12,500 shekels on average, compared to 10,795 in the north and 10,135 shekels in the south.
From a gender point of view, the average wage gap between women and men, which can also be explained in the type of work and the volume of hours, was maintained and stood at 36%.
Men earned 13,295 shekels, compared to women's wages of NIS 9,740.
Trying to get back to the furrow
On the business side, lateral growth was recorded in almost all sectors of the economy, and businesses craved working hands.
Thus, the supply of jobs increased by 50% and registered a record of more than 40,000 jobs in Oljobs.
A survey conducted by the site among employers found that 50% were optimistic about their economic status in 2022, 30% of whom indicated they intended to increase total recruits, but 72% understood that they would have trouble doing so this year.
The largest supply was for jobs without experience - and such there were more than 58 thousand on the site.
They were followed by customer service and administration positions with about 44 thousand jobs in each field, sales and software with 41 thousand jobs each, teaching and education with 24 thousand vacancies, and warehousekeepers still in demand for 19 thousand vacancies.
Einav Boimfeld, Director of Research and Content at OlJobs: “Job seekers are trying to get back into furrow but are not storming the market, mainly due to the lack of attractive jobs in their eyes.
Also, the prolonged dissociation from the cycle of work makes it difficult for them to return, and some have found creative ways to earn a living.”
CBS: Unemployment rate in Israel rose to 6.3%
Bureau survey data shows that about 270 thousand Israelis remained out of work in December 2021.
In November, there were 262,000 unemployed
The percentage of unemployed people in the first half of December 2021 was 6.3%, about 270 thousand Israelis, compared to 6.1% in the second half of November 2021 (about 262k).
This is what data from the personnel survey for the first half of December 2021 by the Central Bureau of Statistics shows.
