State Auditor's report: The actual budget for most years of the Drug Basket Committee operation - smaller than the recommended budget
According to the report by Netanyahu Engelman, for more than 20 years of the basket's activity, the Ministry of Health has not supervised the activities of the committee.
The report also states that the conference protocols are published significantly late, if at all •
The auditor also recommends increasing transparency of subcommittee activity — and updating bin work procedures •
Another flaw found concerns that since the commission began operations, the Ministry of Health has not asked the HMO for reports on the extent of the use and utilization of the drugs in the basket — which would have made it possible to analyze and review the budget given to them.
The Pharmaceutical Basket Committee is one of the most influential public committees on our daily lives and our health.
Every year, the Commission decides on new drugs that will be given to the public free of charge through the HMO — but a new report by the State Auditor published Tuesday warns that this has been operating for more than 20 years without control reports on its activities and without the Ministry of Health and the Health Board monitoring and reviewing its activities.
Israel Hayom correspondent Ran Reznik adds that the State Comptroller's investigation was conducted following the ongoing exposures in Israel Today about the drug basket blunders.
According to the report by Netanyahu Engelman, he recommends “carrying out in the process of expanding the basket corrections and improvements, which will result in a more qualitative extraction of the health care basket budget that the public is entitled to.”
Throughout the years of the existence of the drug basket supplement mechanism, in 2021-1998, NIS eight billion drugs were added to the state budget — with the supplement fluctuating annually in amounts ranging from 0 to 500 million shekels.
In 2019, 2020 and 2021, applications were submitted to add 800 new drugs and technologies to the healthcare portfolio, at a total annual cost of more than NIS 2 billion.
In practice, the budget allocated to expand the basket was smaller than the volume of requests.
In most years of committee operation (90% of the time), the amount of budgetary increment was less than 1.5% of the health basket, a rate recommended by various committees as the desired supplement rate.
The auditor notes that it is necessary to review and regulate the height of the annual supplement with the aim of enabling certainty and long-term planning.
Engelmann further noted that “the model of transparency in the basket work is lacking.”
Thus, for example, the procedure for the work of the basket committee states that the minutes of the meetings, which are closed to the public, will be published within 60 days, but in practice the protocols are published with a delay of 160-109 days, when sometimes the protocols of the final meetings are not published at all.
“The delay in the publication of the protocols impairs the transparency of the decisions; due to this, the ability of the proposal responders — patient organizations and pharmaceutical companies — to submit repeated requests as soon as possible and relevant, having produced lessons from rejecting their proposals, analyzed the reasons for their failure in the previous round, improved and revised their proposals, and reevaluated the feasibility of receiving them in the next round,” the auditor noted in the report.
“The Ministry of Health must publish the protocols in accordance with the schedules set out in the procedure.”
Out of thousands of submissions -- only one economic comment was submitted
Another criticism of Engelmann concerns the preliminary procedure of evaluating the technologies submitted to the drug basket.
The auditor found that about half (46%) of the technologies submitted did not pass this stage, but the Ministry of Health does not publish the reasons for rejection.
Another impairment concerns the activities of the Pharmaceutical Basket Subcommittee which is closed to the media and the public, and in which patient numbers and costs of medicines are discussed.
The auditor recommends attaching a public representative or examining the possibility of making public the discussions without confidential commercial details.
The procedure by which the Health Services Basket Committee operates, it is determined that “an economic assessment must be submitted” to the request to add a drug to the basket.
But in practice, over the years, only one economic assessment has been submitted out of thousands of submissions -- and the committee makes its decisions without an economic assessment.
For example, for the Basket Committee hearings for 2021-2019, applications were submitted to add anti-obesity drugs to the basket.
The report revealed that no economic estimates were attached to the requests, including an estimate of the amount that could have been saved due to reducing the damage of diseases derived from obesity or the ability to avoid gastric shortening surgery.
It also suggests that the decisions of the Pharmaceutical Basket Committee were inconsistent with the objectives and strategy of the Ministry of Health.
Thus, for example, the Ministry of Health defined preventive medicine and preparedness for the treatment of chronic diseases in 2019 as objectives, but in the framework of decisions regarding the expansion of the basket, no emphasis was placed on the need to achieve these goals.
The auditor also warns that since 2011, services that are not the responsibility of the health funds, including rehabilitation and mobility devices and various vaccines, provided by the Ministry of Health (the “third supplement”) are included in the basket of medicines.
This is when the legal framework for this step is regulated only retrospectively.
Over the past six years, NIS 74 million of the drug supplement has been used for these services.
Engelmann recommends that the Ministry of Health update the basket work procedures and also determine whether a separate monetary supplement is needed for these services.
About a third of new drugs that enter the drug basket are defined as “drugs at no added cost,” the use of which does not cost patients' coffers an additional amount because they replace existing treatment.
The auditor suggests considering the possibility that these drugs will be discussed in a different, shortened course, so that the drug basket can be updated several times a year and not just once a year.
The use of particularly expensive drugs is not monitored.
The audit also shows that since the work of the Basket Committee began 20 years ago, the Ministry of Health has not asked the HMO to report and has not supervised the scope of the use and utilization of the drugs in the basket, information that could have allowed the Ministry to analyze and audit the budget given to the funds.
Over the years, only two reports have been published relating to 2009-2006, and these have also been published considerably late (the latter was published this year and dealt with the exploitation of the budget in 2009-2007).
“The delay in conducting tests may lead to difficulty in collecting and analyzing the data, the irrelevance of the conclusions that arise from testing after such a long period of time, to the subcommittee's underpricing, and to make decisions based on non-final findings,” the report said.
Also, the Ministry also does not audit and monitor the uses of particularly expensive drugs and has not carried out the production of lessons.
These are 10 drugs that accounted for 62% of the supplement to the basket (NIS 1.7 billion in 2021-2016).
On this, the auditor wrote: “It is recommended that the Ministry of Health carry out individual controls on these drugs and technologies and analyze the scope of their use compared to the estimates.
Controls and analysis will allow systemic conclusions to be drawn on the working process of the Hessl Committee and the Subcommittee, and on how estimates are prepared when pricing drugs and technologies and their improved technologies.”
