Medical malpractice in the different stages of childbirth
In order to win compensation, the plaintiffs must prove, in addition to the dereliction, that the damage was caused by the same dereliction
Childbirth is one of the most joyful and exciting events in the life of a family.
Unfortunately, however, births sometimes end with serious damage caused to the mother or newborn as a result of the dereliction of medical staff.
In cases where the birth ended in physical harm, to the newborn or the mother, there is room to examine the events that led to the injury and even consider seeking legal advice.
A lawyer specializing in the field of medical malpractice will examine whether there have been defects in the conduct of the medical team during the different stages of birth that have caused the damage and, as he deems appropriate, will consult a medical specialist in the field of relontic.
It should be emphasized that not every error in treatment on the part of the medical staff arises to negligence (in the legal sense of this term) and that various complications during childbirth do not necessarily indicate that its management was negligent.
When then is it negligence?
When the doctor's mistake was due to ineptitude or deviated from the reasonable level of caution, and ineptitude and deviation from the acceptable level of caution caused harm to the patient that would not have been caused if the doctor had not been so.
In this article, we will look at the different stages of childbirth, explain what complications can occur in each of the stages and when they arise to malpractice.
Stage of contractions
The contractions phase lasts an average of 8—14 hours.
At this stage, the cervix gradually opens (in order to allow the passage of the fetus at birth) and at the end of the process should reach a diameter of about ten centimeters.
Most cases of medical malpractice in the labor phase deal with the failure to identify fetal distress in preparation for birth, which has caused damage to the newborn, sometimes manifested by cerebral palsy.
Cerebral Palsy (CP):
Cerebral palsy may be caused by non-detection or delay in identifying prenatal asexudation, which manifests itself in a failure to supply oxygen to the fetal brain tissue.
As a rule, monitoring the condition of the mother and correctly deciphering the monitor that monitors fetal heart activity should lead to early detection of the development of fetal distress, which allows the medical team to act quickly and extract the newborn before being irreversibly affected.
Cases in which the medical staff ignores signs that indicate that the fetus has a lack of oxygen or that the staff misinterprets data on the face and in particular the fetal monitor or reacts late to the distress expressed in the monitor may constitute dereliction.
Cerebral palsy may also be caused by umbilical cord prolapse as well as a result of uterine rupture that was not detected in a timely manner.
Even in these difficult events, it is worth finding out whether the medical staff acted properly.
For example, attorney Anna Rafe Lignese, of Caspi Srour & Co. firm, which specializes in representing victims of medical malpractice, says that her office handled the prosecution of a child injured during his birth after the midwife had immobilized the amniotic sac when the fetal head was too high, thus leading to umbilical cord prolapse (when the umbilical cord precedes the fetal head) and impaired oxygen supply to the fetal brain (as a result of pressure of the fetal head on the umbilical cord) and being born with injury to the fetal head) and being born with injury to the fetal brain (as a result of the fetal head's pressure on the umbilical cord) and being born with injury to the fetal head) and being born with injury to the fetal brain (as a result of the fetal head's pressure on the umbilical cord) and being born with injury Severe neurologic.
In another case, the lawyer said that her office filed a claim due to the gross medical negligence of a maternity ward staff at a large hospital who, during delivery, did not detect clear signs that required a real suspicion that the mother was suffering from a rupture of the uterus in the surgical scar area of her previous pregnancy.
The fetus that was ejected through the rupture of its mother's womb into the abdominal cavity suffered severe fetal distress until it was rescued at a late stage when it was at death's door.
Due to severe fetal suffering during his birth, the child was caused by a complex neurological disability.
We emphasize that in order to win compensation, the plaintiffs must prove, in addition to dereliction, that there is a causal link between the dereliction of the medical staff that resulted in the failure to identify the asphyxia and the damage caused to the newborn, that is, that the damage was caused due to said negligence and not for any other reason or cause.
Examination of the causal relationship will be carried out through the examination of medical measures that, according to the medical literature, only in the existence of which there is a causal relationship between the aseptic and the brain injury.
Among other things, the indicators of the level of acidity in the fetus's blood, its apgar scores, the existence of neurological and systemic impairment, etc.
Passing of the fetus
The phase of active birth
The phase of active delivery begins when the opening of the cervix reaches a diameter of 10 cm and ends with the birth of the baby.
Unfortunately, most medical complications occur during this critical stage.
Delay in childbirth and avoidance of performing a cesarean section
In some cases, dysfunctional childbirth develops, i.e., lack of progression of the active birth process.
In such situations, it is customary to perform a cesarean section, in order to avoid various damages that may be caused to the fetus due to the delay in childbirth.
“There are cases in which failure to perform a caesarean section in a timely manner can cause irreparable harm to the fetus,” Attorney Reiff-Ligenza explained to us.
“For example, we conducted a malpractice claim of birth death caused by a significant delay in performing a cesarean section.
Contrary to any recognized medical practice, medical personnel were not educated to identify fetal distress and perform a caesarean section despite the unusually slow progression of childbirth.
The delay in carrying out the operation caused a lot of systemic damage to the birth which finally led to her death near her birth.”
Negligence in vacuum birth
In situations where the mother or fetus is present with a significant danger that requires a particularly rapid termination of childbirth, a vacuum birth is sometimes carried out (empty cohort).
In this process, a vacuum “dome” is attached to the head of the fetus and force-pull the fetus out.
Naturally, this action involves dangers and can cause harm to both the fetus and the mother and therefore requires great care, accuracy and skill.
In these events, medical malpractice may manifest itself in the fact that the doctor does not follow the mandatory guidelines and performs the operation despite the presence of a contraindication, such as when the head of the fetus is too high in the pelvis, or performs it for longer than permitted or when despite the failure of a large number of attempts, the doctor continues and repeats the operation more than the allowed number of attempts.
In those cases if the careless vacuum operation has caused a newborn harm — among other things, it can cause cranial damage and bleeding that can cause brain damage to develop — there is room for filing a tortious claim.
Paralysis named after ERB
Paralysis named after Erb, here is a congenital nerve injury to the brachial plexus (nerve junction that connects the spine to the upper part of the shoulder) and when it occurs during childbirth it is appropriate to check whether the damage occurred as a result of the negligence of the obstetrical team.
The injury is manifested by weakness of the muscles of the hand and can reach up to complete paralysis of the entire arm.
This paralysis is often caused by difficulty in removing the newborn due to the occurrence of 'shoulder ruffle' - an obstetric emergency that occurs when the fetus's shoulders are trapped inside the birth canal after its head has come out.
When should you suspect that paralysis is caused by medical negligence?
In cases where the evaluation of the weight of the fetus indicated that it was a macrosomous fetus, that is, that it is expected to be born with a weight greater than 4.5 kilograms and according to the guidelines it is better to deliver the mother by caesarean section.
When the newborn's weight is over 4 kilograms, consider caesarean section in view of the risk factors including gestational diabetes and the lengthening of the second stage of birth.
In the event that the medical team ignores an abnormal fetal weight assessment or other risk factors and chooses to proceed with vaginal delivery and the risk of shoulder injury and ERB paralysis is realized, there is a reasonable possibility that this is malpractice.
Indeed, in CA 2694/90, the Supreme Court ruled that “the risk that during childbirth shoulder stenosis will occur is foreseeable to one degree or another of accuracy, and the way to prevent shoulder stenosis, where there is concern about its occurrence is to conduct a cesarean section.”
Placental exit phase
Separation of the placenta from the uterus and its exit occurs due to the contraction of the uterus after the newborn leaves and is accompanied by bleeding.
The process lasts in most cases up to half an hour from the moment the baby is left and, for many times, occurs spontaneously, without the involvement of the medical staff.
After the placenta is out, the medical team will check whether it has come out intact or whether there are parts of the placenta left in the uterus.
Within this stage, complications may occur that can cause serious damage to the mother.
One of the known complications due to the presence of placental residues in the uterus is called “Asherman's syndrome”, scarring of the uterine wall results in inflammation caused by the presence of placental residues in the uterus, a phenomenon that affects the endometrium in a way that does not allow the implantation of pregnancy.
Therefore, in cases where the medical team did not recognize that placental residues remained or did not take all measures to prevent injury to the endometrium despite the suspicion of placental residues in the uterus, it may be medical negligence, and the case deserves a thorough examination by an experienced lawyer in the field.
Death of the mother
The death of a newborn during childbirth is a fairly rare euro.
In these cases, the event that was supposed to bring happiness and joy of life to the whole family becomes, unfortunately, the most tragic event for her.
In some cases, the medical team does not detect bleeding in the mother in a timely manner or react late to such bleeding.
“For example... “, Attorney Reiff-Lignza told us, “our office filed a lawsuit regarding the death of the birth, when in that case the medical staff ignored and did not respond to the mother's alarming vital signs, extended hours, and was late in diagnosing massive and uncontrollable bleeding that occurred as a known complication of the comorbidities from which she suffered.”
“In another case... “, Adv. Reiff-Lignese said, “Our firm represented the relatives of a girl who died after the birth of twins due to bleeding whose origin was in the caesarean section that was not properly sutured.
In the same case, the mother complained of severe pain and weakness after surgery, but the medical team did not properly address her complaints and clinical condition, responding late only after her body systems began to collapse, which resulted in her passing.”
Loss of uterus
In severe cases, birth medical malpractice can lead to hysterectomy, says attorney Rafe Lingze: “Our firm conducted a lawsuit against a hospital underlying hysterectomy due to postpartum medical malpractice.
In the same case, the mother, a young woman of 31 years old, lost her mercy due to lack of proper care in the massive bleeding observed by the medical team after birth and despite this, the actions that could have prevented the damage were not taken in time.”
What are the compensations that are terminated in claims for medical malpractice at birth?
Newborn compensation for injury due to malpractice at birth includes many damage components, with the most significant amounts being provided for pain and suffering, nursing and paid care, salary and pension losses to the victim and even his parents, and other damage components.
The remit compensation to an injured minor for wage and pension losses is calculated in most cases on the basis of the average salary in the economy.
The compensation also includes medical expenses, the cost of medical and rehabilitation accessories, the cost of adjusting housing to the needs of the baby, mobility and more.
“The amount of compensation is determined in each case individually and according to its circumstances,” says Adv. Reiff-Lignese, adding that “today most of the claims on the grounds of medical malpractice end with a compromise that weighs the chance and risk that each party has in conducting the procedure,” but the attorney added, saying that “there are cases in which the procedure is terminated only in a judgment, so if the claim is not rejected, the plaintiffs will receive full compensation for all their damages and for example “As part of a lawsuit conducted by our office, the District Court ruled that a minor caused cerebral palsy due to a delay in identifying fetal distress compensation in excess of ten million shekels.”
concluding
