This is the reason for the prevalence of the eye disease keratoconus in the south
A study revealed that there is a link between the development of the disease and close marriage •
The highest prevalence was found in the Bedouin sector •
Expert: “It is possible that in every sector with many weddings between cousins, we will find a high incidence of disease.”
Keratoconus is a hereditary eye disease that causes some visual impairments.
It is very important to diagnose it as soon as possible, and to find correct solutions to prevent the condition from worsening.
In recent years, several studies have been conducted that help to understand how the disease develops, and innovative therapies have been developed.
The new studies give research to the suspicion of the eye disease Keratoconus being a genetic disease.
Recent research, which dealt with transforming the shape of the cornea from a dome to a cone, revealed that the cause of the cornea's disease and weakness and its distortion of shape is associated with an enzymatic imbalance, following which free radicals can damage the proteins in the cornea - and its structure will change.
The source of that lack of enzymes is genetic, a fact that reinforces the hypothesis that keratocanus is a hereditary disease.
According to Prof. Ariela Gordon-Shag, head of the Department of Optometry Sciences at Hadassah Academic College, “In a study published in the field among Arab students in Haifa, a prevalence of keratoconus was found of 3.2%.
The highest incidence was in students from the Bedouin sector — 20% were with keratoconus, but there was a small relative sample.”
The researcher added that it was an unsurprising finding: “There is a large prevalence of keratoconus in the Bedouin sector.
In our studies we found that close marriage is a risk factor for keratoconus disease.
Thus in any sector with a lot of weddings between cousins, we may find a high incidence.”
In this regard, it should be noted that this is an important finding given the unequivocal conclusion: in cases where a family story of keratoconus disease appears, all family members should approach an appropriate eye examination as soon as possible.
According to Arza Fruchter, B.Sc clinical optometrist, “There is a tenfold recourse to the clinic from remote peripheral areas, mainly from the southern region, compared to the center.”
“Over the past decade, I have noticed that most patients have been evacuated from the periphery, especially from the Beersheba region.
This is mainly due to the high prevalence of marriages within the family (especially in the Bedouin sector) and various allergies, and a lack of awareness of proper handling of the problem.”
So how is the disease diagnosed?
Fruchter explains that keratoconus usually develops in adolescence or late teens (ages 16-15 or 20).
The disease involves a decrease in vision, in parallel with an increase in the cylinder.
Keratoconus patients indicate distorted and/or blurred vision of figures and objects.
These signs worsen with the development of the disease, which usually develops slowly and progressively over years.
However, the disease may also develop at a rapid rate and reach its peak in just a few months.
Many of the patients even indicate increased sensitivity to light.
