Popular terrorism focuses on harming civilians and aims to undermine the sense of security needed to lead a normal life of a civilian population.
The severe wave of attacks that occurred this year, with attacks in Beersheba, Hadera, Bnei Brak, Ariel, Elad, and especially the one that took place in early April on the busy Dizengoff Street in the heart of Tel Aviv, by a terrorist embedded in a crowd, led the police to think creatively to develop a tool that could be used to train fighters to storm terrorists within the civilian population.
The thinking craft was led by the Training Division of the Police and Border Patrol.
These emerged in a competition in the various police districts under the title “Leading Commanders Learning”, in which each district was required to develop measures to help improve the policing and combat skills of fighters, police officers and commanders.
As part of the competition, and as a response to the need to practice Border fighters for fighting in traffic shooting training and such descriptors, Assaf Ben David, Border Terrorism Combat Instructor in Jerusalem, developed the Assaf Facility, consisting of a dynamic target, attached to a telescopic rod mounted by a carrier that can be harnessed to an instructor.
Their servant who guides the carrier to our death, he can practice the fighter standing in front of him by controlling and moving the target to different sides and ranges.
It should be emphasized that in recent years, Border Patrol fighters and fighters have faced numerous attacks in which the perpetrator, carries out shootings and poses a threat while moving through scenes rife with innocent civilians.
“Assaf Facility”, in its current version, is based on components and parts that are used in various fields.
For example, the telescopic rod that has been upgraded and integrated into the facility, is taken from the field of maintenance and cleaning.
Using the facility it is possible to model shooting in motion within a civilian population at a dynamic target while maintaining eye contact with the object, handling a stop in motion, choosing a path of progress and performing selective firing including the practice of preventing injury to uninvolved.
Major Assaf Ben David, whose facility is named after him, says: “The facility we developed, is a breakthrough in learning and training fighters and policemen.
