Study states: Zoom meetings hurt creativity
Some 2,100 engineers and academics worldwide have been asked to develop solutions to the problem — some in video sessions, some in face-to-face meetings.
The result: Virtual meeting impairs creativity and thinking outside the box •
Study leader at Columbia University: “The visual focus on the screen impairs the idea-making process” •
Consolation Forta: There is no harm to labor productivity or critical thinking.
A large scientific study published recently in the scientific journal Nature examined the impact of video sessions on participants' creativity, compared to in-person sessions.
Unfortunately, it has been found that creativity is indeed compromised in virtual sessions through screens.
The research question - led by Melanie Brooks, an assistant professor at Columbia University - was whether remote meetings using a computer preserve the creativity that exists in office brainstorming sessions, or does the level of creativity and free thinking drop as a result of remoteness.
The study itself began as early as 2016 but received a major boost in the two years of coronavirus, during which many employees moved to work from home.
“People in a personal meeting move around the room, using objects and using them for creative thinking,” Brooks says.
“In a computer session, however, the concentration in maintaining eye contact with others comes at the expense of creative activity in the brain.
The visual focus on the screen reduces cognition.
People are more video-focused when interacting, which impairs the broad and expansive idea-making process.”
The space is reduced.
To examine the results of the experiment and verify whether they would repeat themselves, they tested twice — once at Columbia University and once more in real life — on engineers who knew each other from early acquaintance.
At the university, the researcher divided a group of 602 faculty and students into two parts — in one the subjects were asked to meet personally and develop solutions to the problem, and in the other they were asked to do it through a computer.
At the same time, 1,490 engineers from five countries in Europe, the Middle East and South Asia were asked to divide similarly and solve in a new way a problem presented to them.
In both cases, a decrease in creativity and thinking outside the box was found among those who met virtual on video.
Jay Olson, a postdoctoral fellow at McGill University in Canada and a researcher who deals with ways to measure creativity, was not involved in the study but was not surprised by the results.
In his opinion, within a thinking activity, people often look at their surroundings to help generate ideas, while in a video session thinking converges to the screen and does not expand in a way that facilitates creativity.
“When the people in the same room they look around and see the space, where there are objects and situations that can trigger new associations in them.
In contrast, research shows that relationships through a computer change our attention so that we are more focused in and on the screen, and this way reduces innovation and generating ideas through looking at the environment and thinking outward.”
There is no harm to critical thinking.
However, and before managers run employees back to the offices, researchers note that “working through a computer did not harm productivity itself nor people's critical thinking of innovative proposals, when they had to choose the best idea from a set of ideas.
That is, the impact is focused on creativity only and not the rest of the forms of working at a computer.”
Prof. Ellen Langer, a professor of psychology at Harvard University, also qualifies the findings.
“There is a difference between just creativity, such as new uses of frisbee (one of the research questions; EG) and work solutions.
It is also possible that when employees are more relaxed after acquaintance, or when they work from home, creativity will improve.”
Both Prof. Langer and Dr. Olson also proposed future research in which such sessions would be terminated into thinking situations and roaming the room to see how this activity would affect the final outcome.
Also Dr. Olson suggested that following the study only for brainstorming sessions employees would return to work and as a rule he suggested not to be alarmed by one study but to carry out another investigation in the field.
“I wouldn't want workers to be forcibly reinstated and not be happy is a bigger injury” he says.
