A new global study predicts a significant decline in the next 25 years •
The solution: proper management of water reserves
A new and disturbing study published recently in the journal Earth's Future predicts that by 2050 the amount of water available for agriculture will decrease by 80% if the rate of water consumption and world population growth remain within their current usage trends.
In the study, involving scientists from all the world's scientific agencies, scientists summarized the total amount of rainwater, rivers and fresh water sources in the world and compared it to humanity's need for agriculture.
The dismal conclusions of the study show that currently the rate of water consumption has repeatedly doubled in the last 10 years, while at the same time global warming causes rainfall to decrease in agricultural areas around the world.
According to the study's data, 84% of the world's agriculturally designated soils will experience heavy rainwater shortages.
One of the key conclusions emerged from the study calls for farmers around the world to adapt agriculture to climate change and seasons, and switch to growing methods that would make it easier for water to penetrate the soil in order to prevent the process of evaporation of water that would lead to widespread waste of rainwater.
Also, the researchers recommend that farmers working near salt water sources, use rainwater collection technologies in order to prevent it from flowing into the sea.
