We checked: What do the side effects after the coronavirus vaccine say?
Many people who get vaccinated feel weakness, fever, and fatigue after receiving the injection, while others feel nothing •
Could this indicate a stronger immune system of those who do experience these effects, or is it a fundamentally deprived rumor?
While more and more people get vaccinated, the lack of information about the side effects continues to confuse and generate rumors, most of which are not true.
Is the immune system of those who developed side effects stronger than those whose bodies responded less harshly to the vaccine, which could perhaps prove that their system fails to struggle with a foreign body entering the body?
“There are several levels of responses to the vaccine,” says Dr. David Dvir, head of the Division of Primary Medicine at UNITED and a member of the advisory board for the CET (epidemic treatment team), reassuringly: “Headaches, fatigue, pain in place, these are the immediate reactions of the immune system.
This is how the body reacts to the entry of a foreign body into the system”.
Is there a relationship between the levels of antibodies you develop and the side effects?
“There is no correlation between sensations and the development of antibodies against the virus.
About 60— 50% feel the side effects, but about 90% develop protection against the virus.
It was not found that people who developed strong reactions were more protected.”
“In the medical literature, there is no correlation between immediate response and immune level.
In some of the trials where people were also given placebo vaccines, about a quarter of them developed headaches.
It is also a mental component - how the person perceives the vaccine, if he expects there to be side effects.
A lot of the effects that happen could have happened normally as well, but because the public has been vaccinated, it attributes the response to the vaccine itself, and this is the bias you see regarding vaccines in general — attribution of phenomena that happen next to the vaccine and are attributed to it.”
According to Dr. Dvir, the causes of the reported reported phenomena, such as weakness and headache, are not yet known.
Regarding myocarditis (myocarditis), opinions are divided.
“There are all kinds of theories on the subject, but it should be noted that the virus itself causes higher rates of myocarditis than the vaccine.
One of the theories is that it is a strong response of the immune system.”
Is there even a possibility to assess the strength of an immune system?
“When students were exposed to the flu virus, they showed that those who did not sleep or who were under higher stress were more vulnerable to infection.
Apart from this, there are laboratory parameters that test the immune system or its components.
When there is a decrease in the immune system, you see it immediately.
People get a lot of viral or infectious diseases.
It's not like anyone walks around with a weak immune system and isn't aware of it.
These are people who come to inquiries due to repeated events of infectious diseases, and what affects the system are banal things: stress, nutrition, sleep.
By the way, we don't want an immune system that's too strong either, because it can cause autoimmune diseases.”
Soon mRNA vaccines will appear in more contexts, thanks to the vast knowledge that has accumulated about them in recent times.
“There is no doubt that an opening for other vaccines of this kind will be paved.
This technology has been tested for many, many uses beyond vaccines — for treatment of oncological diseases, for example.
Their effectiveness is that the substance stays very little time in the body - enters, does its action, and then breaks down.
This technology isn't new, but it's gotten a serious boost following the very big need for a fast vaccine.
Now, for example, we know that the three-week interval between dose and dose is too small, and some vaccine experts argue that it may be that after a third dose we won't need another vaccine in the near term, so it's unclear whether we go to vaccination every six months or if the third dose will give a larger margin.”
Thousands hurt: Severe privacy default on Route 6
Route 6 customers?
Your private information, including full name, addresses, payment amounts, and full details of your travel, may have been revealed.
According to the Privacy Protection Authority, the Land Road company violated the Privacy Protection Act and its regulations.
After a report passed by the Derech Eretz company, the operator of Route 6 in Israel, about a security incident that occurred at the company, the Privacy Protection Authority began an enforcement process.
As part of the incident, security weaknesses were discovered on its payments website, which allowed the disclosure of a lot of information from the invoices of the member's customers, which were exposed in plain sight.
Among other things, customers' payment invoices were disclosed over a short period of time and these invoices included personal information, including first and last name, payment amounts, vehicle location, travel dates and at what times.
In addition, since the Land Road Company did not properly record access to its systems, it is not possible to know precisely for what period of time non-authorized entities could access the company's systems.
In the breach letter provided by the Privacy Protection Authority to the company, the Authority stressed that most of the largest companies and organizations in the economy are required to adopt a dynamic information security policy, and that with the development of threats and risks, the organization has a duty to rigorously review the updated risks and act in accordance with the current security measures in accordance with the nature and nature of the database.
As a result, companies and organizations have the obligation to update their systems and conduct risk surveys and intrusion tests, to examine and prepare for changing risks.
In addition, it is mandatory for companies and organizations to use an automated documentation mechanism and trainings must be conducted for employees, in accordance with the provisions of the Privacy Protection (Information Security) Regulations.
In accordance with the Inspectorate's findings, the Authority determined that the Company violated the provisions of the Privacy Protection Act and its regulations and also required the Company to carry out a number of corrective actions.
From the Land Way Notebook, operator of Route 6 reportedly: “The issue has been dealt with in accordance with the strictest requirements”
